INTRODUCTION TO THE ODES, .... xvilTHE ODES, IINTRODUCTION TO THE CARMEN SECULARE AND THE ERODES, J I ,I 91THE CARMEN SECULARE, c 94THE EPODES, I 96INTRODUCTION TO THE SATIRES, 115THE SATIRES, 121INTRODUCTION TO THE EPISTLES, I 205THE EPISTLES, 209THE ART OF POETRY, , , 276No ancient author has given in his writings more facts than Horace has done, from which a biographer can construct the story of his life.
These notices are introduced incidentally and in no ostentatious manner.
They come in quite natur­ ally, and without offence to good taste.
From them we learn that Horace's father was a libertinus, or freed slave, a member of the Horatia tribus in Apulia, as is supposed-hence the name.
The future poet was born in 65 B.C. at Venusia, now Venosa, in Apulia, on the confines of Lucania, and so he says of himself " Lucanus an Appulus anceps."
Why he was called Flaccus is not known.
As his father gained his freedom before the boy's birth, young Horace was an ingenuus, or freeborn Roman citizen.
His father was a coactor, that is, either a collector of taxes for the state, or one who took the payments at auction sales.
Whatever his occupation may have been, he seems to have early laid past a little money, which enabled him to buy a small property at Venusia, and to give his son the education of a Roman gentleman.
1
We know nothing of his mother individually.
She had probably died when he was very young.
At all events he makes no reference to her, except as one of his parents, with whom he was quite content, and whom he would not have changed for greater and richer ones if he had had the choice.
2
She may have been to him the type of that Apulian woman whom he praises in Epode ii.
39, sqq.Horace's early education was conducted at Rome under Orbilius Pupillus of "thrashing notoriety," with whom he studied grammar and some of the old Latin authors.
He also read Homer with the same master, and acquired with various teachers some of the modern accomplishments" of those days, such as music and rhetoric.
But Horace's father was not content that his son should finish his education under Orbilius.
Athens was in those days the University of the world, and to Athens accord­ ingly the lad was sent, when he was about twenty years of age, to study philosophy and literature, and to improve himself in Greek.
There he met many young men belonging to the best families in Rome, pursuing their higher education as he was, and with some of them he formed a lifelong friendship.
There, also, the tenor of his life was suddenly changed by the events that followed on the assassination of Julius Cæsar.
Brutus and Cassius called at Athens on their way to the Eastern Provinces which had been assigned them, and while Cassius went on to Syria, Brutus loitered for a time in the city ostensibly to hear the lectures of some of the philosophers, but really, it would seem, to enlist on the re­ publican side as many as possible of the " young bloods" of Rome then "in residence."
It was here that Horace received his appointment as Military Tribune, for which he was by no means fit.
But his soldier life was of short duration.
The battle of Philippi took place in 42 B.C., and there he was obliged to run for his life, like others, and leave his shield behind, as he tells us in apparent soberness, though it may be a mere joke against himself.
He is the only authority for the occurrence of the un­ soldierly act.
Before he was called off with Brutus to the war he is said to have visited many parts of Greece, to which he has made some passing references in his writings.
When Brutus and Cassius were defeated by Octavianus and Antony, and the Republican party were thoroughly discredited, and the men of law and order came into power, an amnesty was proclaimed, and under its kindly leave Horace among many others returned to Rome.
But he came back penniless and fatherless, as his property at Venusia had been confiscated, and his good old father had passed away, probably during his absence.
But curiously enough he does not refer to the sad event, as we should have expected.
For some time after his return to Rome he seems to have supported himself by " writing, for the booksellers," pieces of a satirical kind which made him many enemies.
But ere long he gained the post of Scribe or Quæstor's clerk, either by purchase or by the interest of friends.
Greater prosperity, however, was in store for him.
He was intro­ duced to Maecenas by Virgil and Varius, probably about 40 B.C.1
It was nine months, he tells us, before Maecenas invited him to his house, but when he once became a guest, he made his way to the heart of the Minister almost imme­ diately, and from that time forth the friends were all in all to each other till death separated them.
During the next year after this he formed one of the party which made the famous "Journey to Brundusium," the events of which are duly recorded in Sat., I. v.Horace had a house in Rome, and a moderate 11 establish­ ment " in which he could receive friends, even Maecenas, with suitable appointments.
But he much preferred a country life, and so spent a large part of the year away from the city.
To this change of residence we owe his beautiful and touching descriptions of scenery, and of honest country people and their simple ways (Epode ii., &c.).
On the other hand, he takes no pains to conceal his dislike of the din and bustle of mighty Rome, and of the vice and frivolity of life in the city as compared with the purity of morals and staidness of character of the peasantry (Ode iii. 6).
The passages in which he treats of the worries of town life and the joys of the country are among the most charming in his writings.
It was about 33 or 32 B.C. that Maecenas gave Horace a present of the small Sabine estate, or farm, to which he so often makes reference.
It lay mostly in the valley of Ustica, about 30 miles from Rome, 12 from Tibur, and 4 from Varia, the nearest small town or village.
Its quiet seclusion had a great attraction for the poet, whom it always if set up " again when wearied with society in Rome, and with all the turmoils and interruptions of the busy town.
There he seems to have spent the happiest days of his life.
1
On the farm he had a steward, eight slaves, and five resident families.
His style of living both in Rome and at his Sabine farm was simple, frugal, and temperate.
In the country he employed his time in reading, writing, strolling about and enjoying the hills, the streams, the woods, and doing a little on his farm or in his garden.
He revels in the pleasures of the place, and speaks with deep affection of the fountain of Bandusia, the stream Digentia, the rocks, the glens, the lowing oxen, and the browsing goats.
He was a lover of nature in all her aspects, and he had a kindly heart for man and for beast.
Praeneste, Tibur, and Baiæ were favourite places with him for a temporary residence.
See his own description of his life in the city in Sat., I. vi. 112, sqq.
In one of his touching Odes (Bk. II. xvii.) he declares that when Maecenas dies he will not remain behind­ they will take the last journey together;
and so it came to pass that Horace died only a few weeks after his faithful friend and patron, to whom he delighted to address ode after ode.
They were buried near one another on the Esquiline Hill.
Maecenas introduced Horace to Augustus, and with him also the poet became a favourite.
It was at the request of the Emperor that Horace composed the Carmen Saeculare for the celebration of the games of 17 B.C.
Of this duty he was,, no doubt, justly proud.
Augustus wished him to become his private secretary, but he declined on the ground of health.
In person he was small of size, and in advancing years rather stout.
In youth his hair was black, but he became early grey:
his eyes were weak and liable to inflammation.
As a young man he was attentive to his appearance, Quern tenues decuere togæ nitidique capilli, but grew rather careless as life advanced.
His temper, by his own account, was hasty, but he was easily appeased.
He had his faults and failings, but even these still leaned to virtue's side.
In some of the Odes he seems to represent himself as a libertine, but these are thought to be mere imitations of his Greek models, and not applicable to his own life.
He never married.
Horace does not pose as a man superior to his neigh­ bours, though he says 11 Odi profanum vulgus," in a special application :
nor does he bore us with his own affairs, but gives us only so much that we should like to hear more.
He often refers to his humble origin, and also to his being the friend of the rich and great, but never in such a way as that we should be inclined to dub him either a " bully of humility," on the one hand, or a tuft-hunter and a snob, on the other.
He is a plain, unsophisticated, sensible man, who gains our confidence by the simple, quiet way in which he refers to himself, his life, and his friends.
The two or three occasions on which he speaks of him­ self somewhat egotistically, as in Ode xx.
Book II., and Ode xxx. Book III., do not outweigh the general and consistent character which he maintains for modest humility.
The former Ode seems to have been a mock heroic reply to an invitation from Maecenas;
and the latter a humorous imitation of similar self-laudations by Sappho and Ennius.
It has been stated in the Life of Horace that after his schoolboy days were over he went to Athens to pursue higher studies in philosophy, and to cultivate a more thorough knowledge of Greek Literature.
In following out the latter object, he seems to have read much of that Lyric poetry of which Alcæus and Sappho were leading repre­ sentatives, and which, it would appear, had a special charm for him.
This, as it turned out, gained him his lasting fame.
When the desire took hold of him to adapt the strains of Italy to the Æolian Muse we know not, as he has not told us;
but it would seem that he had written much after his return to Rome before he began to transfer the metres and subjects of the Greek Lyricists into Latin Odes.
The improvement in his style of writing, which arose from his great practice in satiric composition, induced him, it is said, to put forth all his powers in Lyric poetry, as suiting his taste, and as being a novelty in Rome.
This he did for seven years.
In the first six he sent forth the first three books of the Odes.
A fourth followed soon afterwards.
These Odes, being the product of his riper years, are generally considered to be the most perfect and most polished of his writings, in the matter of form at least.
They give proof of maturity of mind and judgment, of a keen insight into life and its important conditions and relationships, rather than of poetic inspiration of the highest type, or of exuberant imagination.
In the Odes the language is generally polished, the thoughts lucid in conception, the diction terse, and the metres remarkable for beauty and harmony.
But occasion­ ally we meet with phrases and sentences of a prosaic kind, and with extravagances inconsistent with Horace's usual good taste.
When Horace speaks from the heart and with his natural fire, as he does in Odes of a national and patriotic kind, such as the second of the First Book, he rises to real beauty and even to grandeur;
but if his subject has been proposed to him, and he is expected to write " to order," the result is very different:
—and naturally so, as common sense and experience will readily admit it must be.
Horace's first attempts would necessarily be translations, or at least mere imitations, of his Greek models.
Others are independent compositions in Greek fashion, and others again original subjects from the public life of Rome and Italy, or on the private affairs of his friends.
The Odes may be classified as follows:
(i) national and patriotic;
(2) friendly;
(3) amatory.
There are many others of a miscellaneous kind, dealing with the beauties of the country;
with virtues, personal and social, with old Roman character and heroism, and with ancient legends of gods and men.
It is in the first of these that Horace appears to most advantage.
In them he breathes forth in words of fire his ardent love of fatherland and home;
he proclaims with honest pride the past glories of the state;
and with un­ bounded admiration he recalls the uprightness and the honesty of the good old days.
On the other hand, he deprecates in sad and warning tones the defection from ancient standards which he sees is taking place, the decay in morals and in military spirit, and the deterioration of his fellow-citizens in all those qualities which went in olden times to form a Roman of the highest type.
But he is little less happy when he dwells on the charms of rural life and scenes, as in the second Epode, of modera­ tion, of contentment, of the shortness and uncertainty of life, and the inevitable foot of Death, " which knocks alike at poor man's hut and prince's hall."
He felt what he said, and the genuine feeling of a right-thinking man must always show itself to advantage in what he writes.
The teaching and the practice of his excellent father had much to do with the creation in the poet of that respect for goodness and that contempt for tinsel and sham which Horace so powerfully expresses.
His love for the country, his inter­ course with the simple-minded, self-reliant, and pure-living peasantry of the Sabine hills, fostered and intensified in him that spirit of sturdy independence and of admiration for the good and noble which characterises his best poems.
On the other hand, the tendency which that spirit has always shown to degenerate into vulgarity, rudeness, and bluster, was kept down in him by his kindly nature, by his rational common sense, and by the refined society of that literary circle in which he moved at Rome.
His amatory verses, though pretty and graceful, and sometimes exquisite in thought and expression, are wanting in depth of fervour, of devotion, and of high moral feeling.
This is no doubt largely owing to the fact that they are, for the most part, mere adaptations of Greek poems, and did not spontaneously flow out from his own head or heart to any real person towards whom he had the honourable and sincere feeling of love.
A few (a very few) of them, again, are offensive, both in tone and wording.
In Odes to friends, however, Horace is more at home than in those just referred to.
These have the true ring of genuine affection and heartiness of feeling.
As an example of this, the Ode to Varus (II. vii.) may be instanced.
In it there is no reserve in his joyous welcome, no halting in his words of friendly greeting, and no stint or grudge in the offer of his cask of wine.
His whole soul is filled with the earnest desire to receive his old companion in arms with the warmest hospitality, and to do him every honour.
He is even prepared " to play the fool a bit" at this happy meeting.
His Odes to Maecenas, Virgil, Varius, and others of his intimate friends, are equally hearty and sincere.
In such as these his lovable nature shines brightly out in every line.
No less apparent is the master hand when he descants on Nature in her soft and gentle form, or in her wilder moods of storm by land or sea.
He speaks with rapture of Bandusia and its icy draughts;
of brooks that hurry down their tortuous course with babbling noise;
of meadows with their velvet sward and new-blown flowers;
of cool and winding glens where goats have shelter from the Dog-Star heat;
of lovely Tibur with its woods and wimpling rills;
of soft Tarentum and its climate's charms;
and of Galæsus' peaceful stream, "dear to the coated sheep."
He speaks, too, of Garganus' oaks lashed by the eastern gale ;
of restless Hadria and its mountain waves to fury roused by tyrant Auster and his boisterous squalls;
of the torrent river with destructive flood;
of Mount Soracte and its snow-clad peak;
and of Caucasus, whose cliffs and frosts and snows repel the foot of man.
Whatever be his subject, Horace is natural, moderate in tone, graphic in description.
It is little to be wondered at that Horace is a favourite with all his readers, and that his memory is cherished as that of one whom we have intimately known, and whom we still fondly love.
His works are a storehouse of maxims for everyday life, and of quotations fitted for use in almost every department and every phase of human action.
Maecenas, scion of a race of kings, my guardian patron and my cherished pride, some glory in the course to raise Olympic dust in clouds, and them the goal,1 scarce shunned by glowing wheels, and the ennobling palm, raise to the heavens as very lords of earth.
Others are proud of heart if fickle Romans haste to the polls, to vote them honours manifold:
others, if in their barns they hoard whatever is swept from Libyan floors.
Him who is pleased to cultivate his father's fields with hoe or spade, you never will induce by wealth of Attalus to leave his farm, turn sailor, and in ever-present fear to plough Myrtoan seas with Cyprian keel.
The trader, when in alarm he sees the south wind battling with Icarian waves, commends his native village and its quiet plains;
but anon his shattered bark refits, unschooled to bear the pinch of stinted means.
Some scorn not cups of Massic wine, nor do they grudge to steal a portion of the busy day, now stretched at length beneath an arbute green, now by some fountain's gently bubbling spring.
Life in the camp has charms for many, and the trumpets blare, mixed with the clarion's note, and wars to mothers hateful.
Ne'er thinking of his gentle wife the hunter braves the chilly air the livelong night, if by his trusty hounds a stag is spied, or Marsian boar has burst his well-made toils.
Me the ivy crown, badge of the learned brow, admits to converse of the gods:
me the cool grove and airy dances of the nymphs and satyrs far from the vulgar throng remove, if her sweet flute Euterpe does not still, nor Polym­ nia decline to tune her Lesbian lyre.
But if you place my name among the lyric bards, I'll strike the lofty sky with towering head.
