Of the several derivations which have been suggested for the term " Satira," the most feasible is that which refers it to the adjective Satur, and especially to its use in the phrase lanx satura, a dish filled with various first-fruits offered to the gods.
Hence, as applied to literary composition it meant afarrago or medley-a gossipy talk on men and matters.
It is supposed to have had its origin in the humours of the rude "
Harvest Home " of the Italian peasants, at which they indulged in off-hand jests and rough by-play, at the expense of their neighbours.
In course of time this rustic sport was displaced by a regular poem, with singing and dialogue, and so gradually developed into an After-Piece of a farcical kind, called Exodium, acted in later years, as a separate perform­ ance, after Tragedies.
The Romans claimed Satire as " all their own."
They had no Greek model to go by, and no Greek Satiric Poems to translate:
but there is no doubt that the earliest writers of Satire drew largely from the old Greek Comedy.
Didactic Satire is said to be due to Ennius.
Lucilius, how­ ever, improved upon Ennius so much in every way that he was called the "Inventor" of it.
There were four chief writers of Roman Satire—Lucilius and Horace, and their imitators, Juvenal and Persius, but it is with Horace only that we have to deal.
Horace was by nature and by choice a Satirist, and he possessed many qualities which fitted him eminently for that function.
He had a wide knowledge of human nature in its sober and also in its comic aspects:
he was shrewd and observant:
he was possessed of strong common sense, great penetration, clear discernment, and sound judgment.
He had a keen perception of the ludicrous and employed it most effectively to ridicule the weaknesses of his fellow men, as well as their faults and their follies.
He took broad and reasonable views of men and of things, and was free from crotchets and prejudices.
He saw even his own defects, and did not shrink from bringing some of them, at least, before his readers, through the mouth of his slave, Davus, in the seventh Satire of the second Book,-one of the most humorous and most amusing of the whole collection of these “ Sermones," or " Satirae.
"It has been already stated1 that after the defeat of the Republican Party at Philippi, Horace on his return to Rome supported himself by writing, for the booksellers, pieces of a Satirical kind, which unfortunately made him many enemies.
Following his great model, Lucilius, he began by being very severe on his victims.
But he soon had cause to feel that he had taken a false step, and he was wise enough to change his methods in time.
He became more genial and more humorous, and sketched men and their ways with a lighter touch.
His choice of Satiric Composition was a dangerous one for a man who had belonged to the defeated Party of Brutus and Cassius.
Horace could not afford to speak with severity of the leaders of the Imperialists;
and thus no political Satire is found in his writings.
Social and literary topics are his only subjects.
His Satiric powers were directed mainly against the eccentricities and the vices of his countrymen, and the corruptions of taste and of morals which crept in with the increase of wealth.
Avarice and money-grubbing, extrava­ gance of living, profligacy, ostentation, pride, superstition, witchcraft, legacy-hunting, and other phases of a degenerate Age, as seen in a great and wealthy city, came freely under his lash.
But his lash is not too cutting and too personal.
His Satires are placed on an ethical basis :
and he tries to convince his readers, not by invective against the objects of his censure, but rather by good-humoured raillery, and by the ridicule of things stupid and perverse.
Like his excellent and prudent father he points out the true path of duty to all by quoting examples of those who strayed from the right track and came to ruin.
His own gentle nature, together with motives of policy, inclined him strongly to adopt a moderate and even lenient tone in dealing with the blemishes and the vices of his fellow-men.
He is willing to look at things in the best light and in the most indulgent spirit- loath to wound, and willing to be pleased if possible.
None of the old Satirists were so genial and so measured in their words as he.
He was essentially kind-hearted and humane, and did not wish to wound the feelings or the pride of any living man.
In this he was much assisted by the simple method of not introducing the names of men known in Rome in his own day, and of adopting, instead, those already used by Lucilius.
He also coined a few names whose etymology might in some cases suggest the indi­ vidual at whom his shafts were aimed, such as Porcius, the "piggish feeder";
Philodemus the "People's Friend":
Pantolabus, the "Grab-all.
"In some of the so-called Satires there is no censure what­ ever.
The " Journey to Brundusium " indulges in no ridi­ cule, unless it be in regard to the fussy Praetor of Fundi, and the superstition of the simple people of Egnatia.
No. IX.
of Book I. is simply a jocular and cleverly told story of the poet's sufferings from the intrusion of an intolerable bore.
This, in the opinion of most readers, is the gem of the whole collection.
Again Satire VI. of Book II.
is a laudation of the quiet and happiness of a country life as contrasted with the rush and bustle and worries of a residence in Rome.
Hence the title of " Sermones " which Horace applies to the Epistles as well as the Satires is certainly a more appropriate one than Satires.
It is equal to "Dis­ courses," "Talk," "Prose Writings."The First Book of the " Sermones," or Satires, was given to the public about 3 5 B.C., and seems to have brought much undeserved odium on the poet.
He started badly with Satire II.
of Book I., which is very bitter in tone.
Many men for whom it was not intended fancied that they were aimed at.
They felt that the cap fitted, and they put it on, though the author had no intention of singling them out for reproof.
They, in turn, taunted him with his low origin as a freedman's son.
But this experience, as already said, did him much good, and led to his after success.
In Book I.
Horace speaks mainly in his own person, but in II.
he expresses his views through selected characters, such as Ulysses, Tiresias, Ofellus and others;
a device which gives more variety and more dramatic interest to the several Pieces.
For similar purposes he introduces fables, stories, and other illustrative matter, which rest the mind of the reader and relieve it from the strain of contemplat­ ing without interruption, the childish follies and the insane excesses of others :
and which at the same time give point and piquancy to the poet's criticisms.
Thus to illustrate his remarks on the respective merits of the city and the country, he relates the well known fable of the Town Mouse and the Country Mouse, with an elegance of ex­ pression and a choice of diction almost perfect.
Again, referring to his boyhood days, he pays a noble tribute to his good old father for the unwearying care he took to form his mind on right principles, and for the bold resolve he made with regard to his education.
Few things in ancient literature are more grand or more touching than this deserved acknowledgment by a grateful son to a far­ seeing and unselfish parent.
Book II., published probably about 30 B.C., shows more of the work of a master hand than Book I.
The judgment is more mature, the tone more vivacious;
the finish more perfect, and clearness of statement more apparent.
There is also an air of greater dignity, and an evident conscious­ ness of success, and of an assured position in literature.
The moralist will find in Horace, and especially in the " Sermones " a wondrous store of gems of practical wisdom and maxims for the guidance of conduct:
and the man of the world may fill his capacious note-book with telling quotations applicable to the affairs of everyday life in all its phases.
The works of Horace are a " possession for all time," and will remain in favour with thoughtful and good men through every age.
