next we beheld some blackbirds served, with breasts quite scorched, and pigeons with no rumps, all nice enough, if the host would only leave untold the cause, and nature of the things.
Him we thus took vengeance on and fled, that not an article we touched, as if on them Canidia, more fell than Afric snakes, had blown with tainted breath.
The Epistles are universally acknowledged to be the most perfect in diction, in metre, in style, and in polish, of all the writings of Horace.
Most of them, if not all, were written, it would seem, in his more mature years when his great practice in composition had prepared him for his highest effort.
The train of thought is that of a refined and educated man, conscious of his powers, and not afraid to declare his opinions, and submit them to the judgment of the world.
The Epistles abound in excellent matter, and are especially conspicuous for their high moral tone.
They have been called 11 the poetry of manner and society," and justly so.
They treat of difficult social and personal affairs with rare discrimination and consummate tact, and give token of greater seriousness and calmer reflection in coming to conclusions than his other works afford.
One sees throughout them the same Horatian characteristics as have been met with in the Odes, the Epodes, and the Satires­ his patriotism, his love of the country, his admiration of virtue, and his detestation of all that is mean, ignoble, or snobbish;
his advocacy of moderation in all things, and his condemnation of the follies, the extravagance, and the lusts and luxuries of his day, are clearly read between the lines" in his Epistles.
These Epistles are not Satires, but they serve an equally good purpose.
It has been said that while the Satires show what is wrong, the Epistles teach what is right.
Thus they are, in one sense, a continuation and a filling out of the Satires, but are more concerned with individual men, and special subjects and incidents.
The masculine good sense which is found in the Satires makes itself as conspicuous in the Epistles, and renders them as instructive and as appreciable to the reader of to-day as if they were written by a modern author not far removed from our times.
In fact, they are human and cosmopolitan.
They are more free than the Satires from obscure allusions, and their teaching goes at once to the understanding and the heart.
The poet is the same " dear old Horace " with whom, after two thousand years have held his ashes in the urn, we still can chat, and laugh, and sometimes almost weep with him in his more pathetic moods.
Horace had a soul for man, his joys, his cares, his woes.
His motto seems to have been—“
Homo sum ;
nil humani a me alienum puto.
”The term Epistulæ is not one given by the poet himself, though he uses the word once, Book II., ii, 22.
He ranks the so-called Epistulæ among his Sermones, or Prosaic poetry.
These, as was said of the Satires, are chatty, gossipy notes on men and things in a light, friendly, con­ versational style, such as a letter of the present day might exhibit.
In some cases they are letters proper, such as XV., in which the poet asks a friend as to the merits of some health-resorts;
No. V. is simply an invitation to dinner;
IX.
a letter of introduction for Septimius to Tiberius Nero;
XIV.
remonstrates with his steward at the Sabine farm in regard to his discontent with country life.
Some of them have a good deal of the Satiric in them, and some of them a touch of irony, but all of them display much of that bonhomie which marked Horace in all his dealings with his fellow man.
In the Epistles, more than in the Satires, Horace charms our imagination and wins our affec­ tions.
When he makes any reference to the faults or weak­ nesses of friends, he does it with a delicate good humour, full of sympathy and tenderness of feeling.
In the Second Book of the Epistles, the subjects are not moral and social, but literary and critical.
In the First, addressed to the Emperor Augustus, the author defends the Classical School of Latin Poetry," combats the idea that age and not real excellence should be the test of poetry, and predicts with confidence that in process of time the national literature would, slowly perhaps but certainly, attain the highest name.
The Second Epistle, to Florus, gives the poet's reasons for abandoning Lyric Composition.
The Third and most famous of these Literary Epistles is that addressed to the Pisos.
It is not known who gave it the title of " Ars Poetica ”—certainly not Horace himself.
Probably it was one of the Scholiasts or one of the early grammarians.
It was evidently not intended as a complete Treatise on the Art of Poetry, but simply as a friendly letter to Piso and his two sons, the elder of whom, it is supposed, was about to venture on the publication of some poetry he had composed.
Horace's " Ars Poetica " simply gives a brief sketch of the Greek Drama, and states the principles of criticism which should be applied to it.
It accords well in subject and treatment with the two Epistles which precede it.
Horace's remarks on some questions of an aesthetic character are marked by his usual independence of judgment and sound common sense.
