I, for my part, do not see of what avail would either study be without a true poetic vein, or what genius wanting culture could effect:
thus each demands the other's aid, and so in friendly union they combine.
He who is eager in the race to reach the wished-for goal, even while a boy has much endured and practised much, has borne extremes of heat and cold, has abstained from love and wine :
he who at the Pythian games plays on the flute has learned the art before, and borne a master's stern rebuke.
But now 'tis quite enough to say, "I make wondrous poems :
plague take the hindmost;
'tis a shame for me to stay behind and to confess, I really know not what I never learned.
"Just as the salesman draws a crowd to buy his wares, so the poet rich in land, rich in invested funds, invites his flatterers to come for gain.
But if he's one who can afford to serve in style a dainty meal, and bail the poor and needy, and free them from the fatal meshes of the law, I shall be astonished if, happy man, he shall come to know the lying, from the honest, friend.
If you, my friend, have given, or mean to give a gift to any one, bring him not, when full of joy, to verses made by you :
for he will exclaim, beautiful!
bravo!
well done!
over some he will no doubt grow pale, will even with loving eyes shed tears, with delight will dance, and stamp the floor.
As those who weep at funerals for hire make almost more lament and more ado than those who from the heart their wailings pour, so does the mocking flatterer show more emotion than the true admirer.
Tis said that kings ply hard with many cups, and put to the test by wine, him whose inner thoughts they wish to know, and see if he deserves their friendship;
if poems you compose, never let thoughts lurking beneath a cunning guise, deceive you.
Suppose that to Quintilius you read a piece, he'd say, " Correct this, I beseech you, and this;
" should you declare, you could not do it better, though you had tried again and yet again with no effect, he would bid you cancel it, and on the anvil place again the verses badly formed.
If, rather than amend the line you chose the blot to keep, he would not spend another word, or waste his efforts, but let you hug both self and work, without a rival and alone.
The man of honesty and sense will censure verses void of pith, will blame the harsh, the inelegant will cross and smear, will prune away all florid ornament, will bid you to make clear what is obscure, will challenge the equivocal, will mark what should be changed;
will become, in fact, an Aristarchus out and out:
he will not say, " Why should I hurt the feelings of a friend for trifles ? "
These trifles will bring to serious trouble him who has once been fooled, and with uncandid warmth received.
As all shun him whom a malignant itch affects, or jaundice, or frenzied craze, or moonstruck madness, so men of sense avoid, and even flee, the crackbrained bard;
the boys torment him, and follow on, heedless of risks.
While he with head in air, belches his verses forth, and strays about, if like a fowler, on his game intent, he falls into a well or pit, although he shout to reach afar, 11 ho citizens, come to my help," not one would care to take him out.
If any one does care to aid him and let down a rope, I should say, " How know .you if on purpose he jumped in, and would rather not be saved ?
and I will tell how the Sicilian bard, Empedocles, came by his death.
While wishing to be deemed a god, he leaped into burning Ætna, " calm and cool."
Let poets have the right and liberty to perish if they wish.
He who saves a man against his will, is just as bad as he who kills him.
For not once only has he acted thus, nor if you bring him back, will he at once become a reasonable man, and lay aside the love of a notorious death.
Nor does it quite appear why he should verses make:
whether he has defiled his father's grave, or impiously disturbed some cursed spot1 ;
at any rate, he's mad:
and like a bear, if he can burst the bars which guard his cell, this merciless reciter puts to flight learned and unlearned alike;
but if he catches one, he holds him fast, and by his reading kills,-a very leech that wont let go the flesh till he is filled with blood.
